[log] bash[68] stdout ## Detailed Implementation Nodes of Functions
[log] bash[68] stdout ### Node 1: Basic Expression Evaluation
[log] bash[68] stdout **Function Description**: Handle basic Python expressions, including basic data types such as numbers, strings, and boolean values.
[log] bash[68] stdout **Core Algorithm**:
[log] bash[68] stdout - Parse numerical literals
[log] bash[68] stdout - Process string literals
[log] bash[68] stdout - Evaluate boolean values
[log] bash[68] stdout - Support basic operators
[log] bash[68] stdout **Input/Output Examples**:
[log] bash[68] stdout ```python
[log] bash[68] stdout from asteval import Interpreter
[log] bash[68] stdout # Basic numerical expressions
[log] bash[68] stdout interp = Interpreter()
[log] bash[68] stdout result = interp("4")
[log] bash[68] stdout print(result)  # 4
[log] bash[68] stdout result = interp("'x'")
[log] bash[68] stdout print(result)  # 'x'
[log] bash[68] stdout result = interp("b'x'")
[log] bash[68] stdout print(result)  # b'x'
[log] bash[68] stdout result = interp("str(4)")
[log] bash[68] stdout print(result)  # '4'
[log] bash[68] stdout result = interp("repr(4)")
[log] bash[68] stdout print(result)  # '4'
[log] bash[68] stdout # Boolean value handling
[log] bash[68] stdout result = interp("...")
[log] bash[68] stdout print(result)  # Ellipsis
[log] bash[68] stdout result = interp("False")
[log] bash[68] stdout print(result)  # False
[log] bash[68] stdout # Variable assignment and access
[log] bash[68] stdout interp("x = 8")
[log] bash[68] stdout result = interp("x")
[log] bash[68] stdout print(result)  # 8
[log] bash[68] stdout # Test verification
[log] bash[68] stdout assert interp("4") == 4
[log] bash[68] stdout assert interp("'x'") == 'x'
[log] bash[68] stdout assert interp("False") == False
[log] bash[68] stdout ```
[log] bash[68] stdout ### Node 2: Dictionary Indexing
